(
<figureCitation box="[602,724,480,505]" captionStart-0="Figs 61–64" captionStart-1="Figs 65–70" captionStartId-0="14.[133,170,1637,1656]" captionStartId-1="15.[133,170,1172,1191]" captionTargetBox-0="[137,1153,760,1601]" captionTargetBox-1="[137,1158,220,1143]" captionTargetPageId-0="14" captionTargetPageId-1="15" captionText-0="Figs 61–64. Megaselia turkuensis n. sp. male: 61 – postpedicels (ruptured), palps a proboscis; 62 – labellum from below; 63 – notopleuron with cleft; 64 – right side of scutellum." captionText-1="Figs 65–70. Megaselia turkuensis n. sp. male: 65–67 – hypopygium; 68 – front tarsus; 69 – hind femur; 70 –wing." figureDoi-0="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6252187" figureDoi-1="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6252189" httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/6252187/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/6252189/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="25">Figs 61–70</figureCitation>
)
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="14.[133,1154,527,735]" pageId="14" pageNumber="25">
Dia gno sis (male). In the keys to British species (
<bibRefCitation author="DISNEY R. H. L." box="[735,867,527,551]" pageId="14" pageNumber="25" pagination="1 - 155" refId="ref7257" refString="DISNEY R. H. L. 1989. Scuttle Flies Diptera Phoridae Genus Megaselia. Handbooks for the Identification of British Insects 10 (8): 1 - 155." type="journal article" year="1989">Disney1989</bibRefCitation>
) it runs to couplet 260. If one ignores the first part of lead 1 then one is returned to couplet 156. This is the section revised by 
<bibRefCitation author="BUCK M. &amp; DISNEY R. H. L." box="[257,502,588,612]" pageId="14" pageNumber="25" pagination="73 - 154" refId="ref7113" refString="BUCK M. &amp; DISNEY R. H. L. 2001. Revision of the Megaselia giraudii and M. densior species complexes of Europe, including ecological notes (Diptera, Phoridae). Beitrage zur Entomologie 51: 73 - 154." type="journal article" year="2001">Buck &amp;Disney (2001)</bibRefCitation>
, in whose key to males it runs to couplet 2, where neither option applies. However, a note suggests that the unknown male of 
<taxonomicName authority="(Schmitz)" baseAuthorityName="Schmitz" baseAuthorityYear="1919" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="25" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="septentrionalis">
<emphasis box="[951,1154,619,643]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="25">M. septentrionalis</emphasis>
(Schmitz)
</taxonomicName>
might run to this couplet, but it has a yellow haltere knob in contrast to the new species. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="DISNEY &amp; WINQVIST" authorityYear="2018" box="[230,381,680,704]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="25" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="turkuensis">
<emphasis box="[230,381,680,704]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="25">M. turkuensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
fails to run down in 
<bibRefCitation author="BORGMEIER T." box="[640,858,680,704]" pageId="14" pageNumber="25" pagination="1 - 160" refId="ref7080" refString="BORGMEIER T. 1966 (1965). The species of the genus Megaselia, subgenus Megaselia (Diptera, Phoridae). Studia Entomologica, Petropolis 8: 1 - 160." type="journal article" year="1966">Borgmeier’s (1966)</bibRefCitation>
relevant keys to Nearctic species.
</paragraph>
